- VSCode Version: June 2017 (version 1.14)
- OS Version: mac os sierra 10.12.16

Reproduces without extensions: Yes

Steps: 
(names in steps can be changed to another)
1) add folder issue1
2) navigate to the folder using terminal
3) run "dotnet new console"
4) run "code --disable-extensions"
5) Try to add iUser interface and the User class as the following
-------------------
using System;

namespace issue1
{
    class Program
    {
        static void Main(string[] args)
        {
            Console.WriteLine("Hello World!");
        }
    }
    
    public interface IUser
    {
        int Id {get;set;}
        string Name {get;set;}
        List<int> Ids {get;set;}
    }

    public class User : IUser
    {

    }
}

Expected result:
    In a moment when I add List<int> property to IUser - intellisence resolve using for that 
    dependency. Adding inheriting from IUser suggests you to add missing fields and resolving it 
    automatically.  
Actual result:
    No resolved usings and no implemented properties from IUser. And what more interesting that 
    VS doesn't show you that any error exists until you build the project. Using CMD+. doesn't do 
    anything.
![program cs issue1](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/28143505/29174868-38c8c79e-7df0-11e7-8979-46ab468b67dc.png)

There's a really handy feature (they only one from PyCharm I'm missing). If I'm in a deeply nested block, PyCharm will tell me that 
```
def foo(): 
  for i in list:
    # very
    # long
    # code
    if condition:
        # more 
        # long
        # code
        while...: 
    while....:
        if...:
```
that the current cursor position is positioned in hierarchy that way: 
` for i in list | if condition | while ... `

It would be great if VS Code provided such a feature!
